> Look, you have a big fan pushing air out the botton of the bus.  If you
> have a big opening nearby pulling air from the bottom of the bus into the
> engine bay the air is going to take the path of least resistance, which
> means that the air will be recirculated unless there is a big slipstream
> to carry it away.  In addition, the airflow around the rear of a vehicle
> isn't as smooth and predictable as we would like.  You may have gotten
> away with this, but that doesn't mean the the people who follow your
> advice will.
>
George, you have a "theory" that recirculation is a problem with this mod. I
have years of testing on multiple buses that that has never shown any
cooling issues at all. You can argue it all you want I guess, but the proof
is in the pudding.

>
> Yes, you've done the tests but what was the engineer's intent for the
> acceptable pressure drop through the intake ducts?  Unless you have
> happened upon a VW cooling engineer's notebook I doubt that you know any
> more about that than the rest of us.

First hand experience has shown me that the more you reduce engine bay
vacuum (and if you can, create pressure with scoops), the cooler head and
oil temps run. Why do I have to have an engineers notebook to validate that?


> Exactly, and the baywindow scoops don't stick out enough to get out of the
> boundary layer.

Interesting how you came to that conclusion. Then how come at 4000rpm while
sitting still, I can pull water 3 inches up a tube with the engine bay
vacuum, and if i'm doing 4000rpm at 75mph, my engine bay has enough pressure
to force the air 1/2" below the water level? The awnser is simple, the scoop
design works, and works very well at that. George, you've never tested for
vacuum/pressure in aVW engine bay, so you have no ground to stand on. I
have.
