I've done a lot of bus cruises that cover dirt roads. My engine bay
collected no more dirt than any of the others on our cruise. A true side by
side comparison if you will. Same drive and all. Again, "theory" taking a
back seat to actual testing. Are you starting to see a pattern here, George?


> When I said "quick fix" I was referring to the simple discarding of the
> front tin.  I have much less problem with well-engineered modifications,
> such as cooling air ducted through the front tin from the front of the
> bus.  At least in this case, the modifier considered a way to achieve the
> desired result without causing other problems.

No offense to anybody, but "well-engineered" is not the correct term. The
reason that mod works is because it relieves the intake restriction to the
engine bay. People that do this mod have the idea that they are providing
"cool air" into the engine bay with it. It does lower the engine temp, but
not because of how they think its working. "Well-engineered" means they know
how and why it works.

