>
> I suggest that you check to see what work I _have_ done before making
> such accusations.  This topic has been discussed previously although
> the discussion centered upon missing engine bay seals, not discarding
> the front tin.  I measured the difference in inlet and engine bay
> temperatures and found the delta T to be about 3C under the
> same conditions with good seals.  The important result was that missing
> engine seals make a _big_ difference in engine bay temperatures, on the
> order of 10-15C, due to recirculation.  Whether you acknowlege it or not,
> recirculation can occur.

Again, ZERO experience with engine bay vacuum/pressure. You've measured
engine bay temperature compared to outside air temp? Big whoop-idy-doo,
that's not vacuum/pressure testing like I pointed out. I've gone another
step further than you have though with engine bay vs. outside air temp. I've
measured that difference of engine bay vacuum vs. outside air temp with the
front tin missing, and with the front tin installed. Do you want to know the
results, or do have a theory and no matter what figures I got from actual
testing you'll argue it anyway? Ah, what the hell, i'll tell you anyway.
With the tin installed, the air temp entering the fan (that's where I put
the sensor) was 20-25 degrees hotter on the highway than the outside air
temp. Want to guess what it was with the engine tin removed? The air temp
going into the fan was the exact same as the outside temp. Interesting. Even
sitting parked in stop and go traffic where your "theory" of recirculating
air is the issue, the air temp into the fan didnt' increase. Now, I do have
a "theory" for you. I think the reason for the increased airtemp going into
the fan came because of the engine bay vacuum all the stock tin provides.
Even if you have all you tin and seals in place, there are still small
airgaps that hot air from underneat can come through, and if the engine bay
is under vacuum, then it is pulling hot air from anywhere it can to feed the
fan.

